Across all three domains, ABIscope successfully generated and evaluated a total of 1,462 test cases, among which 806 were identified as exposing at least one ABI incompatibility issue. The IO domain reached the 500-binary cap and stopped early, while FS and Mem ran until the 6-hour wall-clock budget was exhausted, explaining the slightly different totals across domains. The FS domain demonstrates the highest incompatibility rate at 86.8%, reflecting the complexity of VFS-layer semantics and the large number of flag combinations generated by the LLM-based mutations. The IO domain has the lowest rate (16.4%), attributable to the comparatively simpler argument space of I/O primitives. Memory management falls between the two at 63.6%, driven primarily by the intricacy of `mmap` flag validation and `madvise` advice semantics.

== Filesystem Syscall Compatibility <sec-results-fs>

Against Asterinas, 420 of 484 cases (86.8%) are incompatible. The detailed breakdown by incompatibility type is:

#align(center)[
#table(
  columns: (auto, auto),
  align: center,
  [*Incompatibility Type*], [*Cases (FS)*],
  [`errno_diff`],           [386],
  [`behavior_diff`],        [232],
  [`ret_diff`],             [210],
  [`unexpected_failure`],   [65],
  [`unexpected_success`],   [35],
  [`missing_syscall`],      [2],
)
]

Note that a single incompatible case may exhibit multiple types of divergences simultaneously; consequently, the per-type counts sum to more than 420. `errno_diff` is the dominant signal (386 cases, 91.9% of all incompatible FS tests), indicating that Asterinas and Linux diverge most severely at the error-code level rather than simple success/failure outcome.

=== Errno Mapping Divergences

The single largest root cause is incorrect errno selection in error paths. When `fcntl` is called on an invalid file descriptor, Linux validates the descriptor first and returns `EBADF` (9); Asterinas evaluates the command code first and returns `EINVAL` (22) when the command is unsupported. A similar validation order inversion is observed for `openat` with invalid `dirfd` values: Linux returns `ENOTDIR` or `EINVAL` depending on the flag combination, while Asterinas returns `EEXIST` or `ENOENT` inconsistently. This pattern recurs across `fallocate`, `ftruncate`, and `fdatasync`, where Asterinas's internal error codes are mapped to a generic `EINVAL` rather than being translated to the correct Linux errno value.

=== Missing `openat2` Support
Asterinas return `ENOSYS` (38) for `openat2` (syscall 437), while Linux returns `EINVAL` (22) for malformed arguments. This indicates that `openat2`, introduced in Linux 5.6, is not yet implemented in the Rust-based kernel.

=== File-Descriptor Lifecycle Differences

Asterinas employs different file-descriptor validation logic. When writing to a `fd=0` (stdin) with a zero-length buffer succeeds on Linux, Asterinas returns `EBADF` (9). Some double close sequences which Linux handles through returing `EBADF`, Asterinas instead succeeds silently. `dup2` with an invalid source descriptor returns `ENOENT` (2) rather than `EBADF` (9), consistent with an incorrect internal error translation in the fd-table lookup path. These fd-lifecycle differences will propagate to downstream syscalls and cause further incompatibilities in other areas which rely on the return value or the errno code.


== I/O Syscall Compatibility <sec-results-io>

Against Asterinas, 82 of 500 cases (16.4%) are incompatible. The type breakdown is:

#align(center)[
#table(
  columns: (auto, auto),
  align: center,
  [*Incompatibility Type*], [*Cases (IO)*],
  [`behavior_diff`],        [79],
  [`ret_diff`],             [50],
  [`errno_diff`],           [46],
  [`unexpected_failure`],   [36],
  [`unexpected_success`],   [15],
  [`missing_syscall`],      [3],
)
]

In contrast to the FS domain, `behavior_diff` (79 cases) is the leading signal in IO rather than `errno_diff`, indicating that the two platforms produce different observable side-effects even in cases where the error code matches.

=== `dup2` Returns `ENOENT` Instead of `EBADF`
The most reproducible IO incompatibility is `dup2` called with an invalid `oldfd`. Linux returns `EBADF` (9); Asterinas returns `ENOENT` (2). This is consistent with an incorrect error-code mapping in Asterinas's `dup2` syscall handler: the fd-table lookup path returns an internal "not-found" status that is translated to `ENOENT` rather than to the POSIX-mandated `EBADF`. The same bug affects `dup3` and `fcntl(F_SETOWN)` on invalid descriptors (returns `ESRCH` instead of `EBADF`).

=== `fcntl(F_GETFL)` Missing `O_LARGEFILE` Bit

`fcntl(F_GETFL)` in Asterinas returns a flag mask that is missing the `O_LARGEFILE` bit (`0x8000` on x86-64). Linux's open path sets this bit automatically for all 64-bit file opens; Asterinas either does not set it internally or truncates the flags word during kernel-to-userspace translation. Programs that inspect `O_LARGEFILE` to determine large-file support will incorrectly conclude the file was opened in 32-bit mode.

=== Access-Mode Check Divergence 

`ftruncate` returns `EPERM` (1) in Asterinas for some files that Linux successfully truncates. Concurrently, `pwrite64` on a file descriptor opened `O_RDONLY` sometimes succeeds in Asterinas where Linux correctly returns `EBADF`. While the two divergences manifest in opposite ways, they can be traced back to a common cause: inconsistent permission checks in Asterinas's VFS compared to Linux.

=== Umask and File-Creation Mode Difference

Files created via `open(O_CREAT)` in Asterinas consistently show `st_mode = 0644`, while the same sequence on Linux produces `0664`. This indicates Asterinas applies `umask 0022` whereas the Linux test environment used `umask 0002`. Additionally, `st_uid`/`st_gid` in Asterinas are always 0, confirming that user-namespace credential mapping is not yet implemented.

=== `fdatasync` Stub Behavior

`fdatasync` on uninitialized or non-syncable file descriptors returns `0` (success) in Asterinas, while Linux returns `-1` with `errno = EINVAL`. This indicates that Asterinas's `fdatasync` handler lacks the file-descriptor type check performed by Linux's VFS layer before issuing the underlying sync operation.

== Memory Management Syscall Compatibility <sec-results-mem>

Against Asterinas, 304 of 478 cases (63.6%) are incompatible. The type breakdown is:

#align(center)[
#table(
  columns: (auto, auto),
  align: center,
  [*Incompatibility Type*], [*Cases (Mem)*],
  [`errno_diff`],           [277],
  [`behavior_diff`],        [251],
  [`ret_diff`],             [110],
  [`unexpected_success`],   [64],
  [`unexpected_failure`],   [44],
  [`missing_syscall`],      [1],
  [`unknown`],              [3],
)
]

`errno_diff` and `behavior_diff` are strongly co-occurring: 224 of 304 incompatible cases exhibit both simultaneously, suggesting a systematic pattern in which an incorrect errno is set alongside a divergent observable kernel-side state.

=== `mmap` Validation Order (68 Cases)

File-backed `mmap` with an invalid file descriptor should return `EBADF` (9) on Linux. Asterinas returns `EINVAL` (22) in 68 such cases, indicating that Asterinas validates `MAP_SHARED`/`MAP_PRIVATE` flag consistency and offset alignment *before* checking whether the descriptor is valid. Linux performs fd validity first, so `EBADF` takes precedence. This error-precedence inversion also manifests for `mprotect` and `mremap` with illegal address-range arguments (`ENOMEM` vs `EINVAL`).

=== `madvise` Incomplete Implementation

Three `madvise` advice values: `MADV_PAGEOUT`, `MADV_POPULATE_WRITE`, and `MADV_DONTNEED_LOCKED` are either unimplemented or incorrectly handled in Asterinas. Linux returns `ENOMEM` when the requested advice cannot be satisfied due to resource constraints; Asterinas returns `EINVAL`, representing a resource-exhaustion failure with an invalid-argument failure.

=== Struct ABI and `copy_to_user` Mismatches
In Asterinas, `writev` returns 73,312 bytes for an `iovec` sequence where Linux returns 4,096. This suggests a possible mismatch in how `iovec` lengths are interpreted or accumulated in the copy-from-user path.
`getrusage` reports zeroed `ru_maxrss` and shifted `ru_stime` fields, which is consistent with a potential struct layout or ABI mismatch between the kernel and the userspace libc headers.
In addition, failed `fstat` calls in Asterinas may leave parts of the `struct stat` buffer uninitialized instead of fully zeroing it before returning.


== SAC Coverage Analysis <sec-results-sac>

#ref(<eq-gain>, supplement: [Equation]) and #ref(<eq-update>, supplement: [Equation]) in Section 2 define how ABIscope accumulates global coverage $G_t$ across accepted seeds. Each experiment begins with a bootstrap phase in which all 200 initial seeds are ingested and their feature sets are merged into $G_0$. Subsequent LLM-based mutation iterations then expand the coverage set. The table below compares $|G_t|$ at the end of the bootstrap phase against its value at experiment termination. This quantifies the contribution of the mutation loop.

#align(center)[
#table(
  columns: (auto, auto, auto, auto, auto),
  align: center,
  [*Domain*], [*After Bootstrap \ (200 seeds)*], [*After Mutations*], [*Growth*], [*Mutation Iters*],
  [Filesystem (FS)],     [1,502], [4,383], [×2.9], [302],
  [I/O Management (IO)], [5,131], [11,161], [×2.2], [444],
  [Memory Mgmt (Mem)],   [1,204], [3,226],  [×2.7], [278],
)
]

Even before any mutation, the 200 Syzkaller-derived seeds cover a non-trivial slice of each domain. FS bootstraps at 1,502 distinct feature tokens, a mix of flag co-occurrences, path-string patterns, and the usual numeric boundary constants. IO starts much higher, at 5,131, which is unsurprising given how many arguments syscalls like `dup2`, `ftruncate`, and `fcntl(F_GETFL)` each contribute on their own. Mem reaches at 1,204, close to FS; the flag spaces of `mmap`, `mprotect`, and `madvise` are wide but the seeds only sample a handful of typical combinations.

The mutation loop more than doubles coverage in all three domains. In FS, coverage goes from 1,502 to 4,383 over 302 iterations (2.9×); the five mutation strategies clearly find flag and path combinations that the initial seeds miss. IO ends at 11,161 after 444 iterations (2.2×). The per-accepted-seed yield is about 136 new tokens, roughly 13× higher than FS which we attribute to IO mutations hitting large-offset arithmetic and flag-mask edge cases that the seed corpus barely covers. Mem grows from 1,204 to 3,226 across 278 mutation files (2.7×), suggesting that even simple argument-level mutations on `mmap`, `madvise`, and `mprotect` keep producing novel runtime behavior. Overall, uniform random selection over the five mutation types is enough to keep SAC growing for the full 6-hour budget.